\begin_layout Standard
In each case the row operation can be undone to recover the original matrix.
 This is exactly the idea of an inverse! The six elementary matrices correspondi
ng to the six row operations (the row operations that gave the matrices
 above and the row operations that were used to recover the original matrices),
 in the order encountered are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{gathered}\text{operation }\quad\text{ recovery}\\
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\quad\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 2
\end{array}\right]\quad\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & \frac{1}{2}
\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 3\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\quad\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & -3\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]
\end{gathered}
\]

\end_inset

It must therefore be that each operation matrix is invertible and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{gathered}\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 2
\end{array}\right]^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & \frac{1}{2}
\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 3\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & -3\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]
\end{gathered}
\]

\end_inset

Multiplying the operation matrix by the inverse matrix will verify this
 claim.
 Each elementary matrix has an inverse elementary matrix of the same type.
 And in the case of a row swap, the elementary matrix is its own inverse.
\end_layout

