\begin_layout Standard
Is the determinant of a swap matrix always 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

? There is no such thing as a swap matrix with one row.
 There is only one swap matrix with two rows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and there are only three swap matrices with three rows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right],\ \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 0 & 1\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0
\end{array}\right],\text{ and }\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1\\
0 & 1 & 0
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

It is easy enough to check that all four of these matrices have determinant
 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, so maybe all swap matrices do have determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
