 For example, there are 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{4(3)}{2}=6}$
\end_inset

 swap matrices with 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 rows, and there are 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{100(99)}{2}=4950}$
\end_inset

 swap matrices with 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

 rows.
 The formula 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{n(n-1)}{2}}$
\end_inset

 is a special case of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

choose formula
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which is a formula for the number of ways to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 objects from a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 objects, with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 This number is also known as a binomial coefficient and there are several
 notations for it.
 Common notations and the formula for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 choose 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (a binomial coefficient) are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k
\end{array}\right)=\,_{n}C_{k}=C(n,k)=\frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}.
\]

