\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:determinant-general-expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) makes it relatively straightforward to prove that all swap matrices have
 determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 We have already shown (assuming you did the calculation above) that the
 determinant of any 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix (and there is only one of them) is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 Proceeding by induction, assume that for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq2$
\end_inset

, the determinant of all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 swap matrices is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a particular but arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $(k+1)\times(k+1)$
\end_inset

 matrix where rows 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 have been swapped.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1\geq3$
\end_inset

, there must be a row of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 that is not involved in the swap, say row 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\neq i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\neq j$
\end_inset

.
 Expanding the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 along row 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det S & =(-1)^{\ell+1}S_{\ell,1}\det S_{\backslash\ell,1}+(-1)^{\ell+2}S_{\ell,2}\det S_{\backslash\ell,2}+\cdots+(-1)^{\ell+k+1}S_{\ell,k+1}\det S_{\backslash\ell,k+1}\\
 & =(-1)^{\ell+\ell}S_{\ell,\ell}\det S_{\backslash\ell,\ell}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

because 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\ell,:}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell^{th}$
\end_inset

 row of the identity matrix (not being involved in the swap), meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\ell,m}=0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\neq m$
\end_inset

.
 Since the swapped rows are both in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\backslash\ell,\ell}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\backslash\ell,\ell}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 swap matrix and the inductive hypothesis implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\det S_{\backslash\ell,\ell}=-1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det S=(-1)^{\ell+\ell}S_{\ell,\ell}\det S_{\backslash\ell,\ell}=(1)(1)(-1)=-1,
\]

\end_inset

completing the proof.
