\begin_layout Standard
To begin, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a function from 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrices to scalars satisfying the four properties above.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 also has the following two properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate-Resume
\begin_inset Formula $G(A)=0$
\end_inset

 whenever the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent.
 
\shape italic
Proof:
\shape default
 Because the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent, one of them, say column 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, can be written as a linear combination of the others.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle A_{:,k}=\sum_{j\neq k}c_{j}A_{:,j}}$
\end_inset

 for some constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
G(A) & =G\left(\left[\begin{array}{ccccccc}
A_{:,1} & \cdots & A_{:,k-1} & {\displaystyle \sum_{j\neq k}c_{j}A_{:,j}} & A_{:,k+1} & \cdots & A_{:,n}\end{array}\right]\right)\\
 & =\sum_{j\neq k}G\left(\left[\begin{array}{ccccccc}
A_{:,1} & \cdots & A_{:,k-1} & {\displaystyle c_{j}A_{:,j}} & A_{:,k+1} & \cdots & A_{:,n}\end{array}\right]\right)\\
 & =\sum_{j\neq k}c_{j}G\left(\left[\begin{array}{ccccccc}
A_{:,1} & \cdots & A_{:,k-1} & {\displaystyle A_{:,j}} & A_{:,k+1} & \cdots & A_{:,n}\end{array}\right]\right)\\
 & =\sum_{j\neq k}c_{j}\cdot0=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

by applying properties 3, 4, and 2, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate-Resume
\begin_inset Formula $G(B)=-G(A)$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the result of swapping two columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\shape italic
Proof:
\shape default
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the result of swapping columns 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and without loss of generality, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $i<j$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B=\left[\begin{array}{ccccccc}
A_{:,1} & \cdots & A_{:,j} & \cdots & A_{:,i} & \cdots & A_{:,n}\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\left[\begin{array}{ccccccc}
A_{:,1} & \cdots & A_{:,i}+A_{:,j} & \cdots & A_{:,i}+A_{:,j} & \cdots & A_{:,n}\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Then by repeated application of property 3,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
G\left(C\right) & =G(A)+G(B)\\
 & +G\left(\left[\begin{array}{ccccccc}
A_{:,1} & \cdots & A_{:,i} & \cdots & A_{:,i} & \cdots & A_{:,n}\end{array}\right]\right)\\
 & +G\left(\left[\begin{array}{ccccccc}
A_{:,1} & \cdots & A_{:,j} & \cdots & A_{:,j} & \cdots & A_{:,n}\end{array}\right]\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 and by property 2 the last two terms are zero as is 
\begin_inset Formula $G(C)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $0=G(A)+G(B)$
\end_inset

, concluding the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To begin the induction proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is unique, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(\left[a\right]\right)=G\left(a\left[1\right]\right)=aG\left(\left[1\right]\right)=aG(I)=a$
\end_inset

 by properties 4 and 1, so 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is uniquely determined for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times1$
\end_inset

 matrices.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is unique for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(k-1)\times(k-1)$
\end_inset

 matrices for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k>1$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a particular but arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 If the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent, then property 5 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $G(M)=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $G(M)$
\end_inset

 is uniquely determined.
 Now suppose the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 are linearly independent.
 By theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Matrix-Characterization-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a pivot in every column.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is square, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a pivot in every row.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a nonzero entry in row 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{k,j}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left[\begin{array}{ccccccc}
M_{:,1}-\frac{M_{k,1}}{M_{k,j}}M_{:,j} & \cdots & M_{:,j-1}-\frac{M_{k,j-1}}{M_{k,j}}M_{:,j}\  & \ M_{:,j+1}-\frac{M_{k,j+1}}{M_{k,j}}M_{:,j} & \cdots & M_{:,n}-\frac{M_{k,k}}{M_{k,j}}M_{:,j}\  & \ M_{:j}\end{array}\right],
\]

\end_inset

repeated application of properties 3 and 4 plus property 6 if needed implies
 
\begin_inset Formula $G(A)=\pm G(M)$
\end_inset

 depending on whether 
\begin_inset Formula $j=k$
\end_inset

.
 Either way, 
\begin_inset Formula $G(M)$
\end_inset

 is uniquely determined if 
\begin_inset Formula $G(A)$
\end_inset

 is.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k,:}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & \cdots & 0 & M_{k,j}\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

, making it sufficient to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $H(B)$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $(k-1)\times(k-1)$
\end_inset

 matrices by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H(B)=\frac{1}{M_{k,j}}G\left(\left[\begin{array}{cc}
B & M_{1:k-1,j}\\
\mathbf{0}^{T} & M_{k,j}
\end{array}\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

is uniquely determined.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $H(B)$
\end_inset

 inherits properties 2, 3, and 4 from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, so it only remains to establish that 
\begin_inset Formula $H(I)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then, by the inductive hypothesis, 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is uniquely determined.
 To that end,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
H(I) & =\frac{1}{M_{k,j}}G\left(\left[\begin{array}{cc}
I & M_{1:k-1,j}\\
\mathbf{0}^{T} & M_{k,j}
\end{array}\right]\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{M_{k,j}}G\left(\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
I_{:,1} & \cdots & I_{:,k-1} & {\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^{k}M_{i,j}I_{:,i}}\end{array}\right]\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{M_{k,j}}\sum_{i=1}^{k}M_{i,j}G\left(\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
I_{:,1} & \cdots & I_{:,k-1} & {\displaystyle I_{:,i}}\end{array}\right]\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{M_{k,j}}\left(M_{k,j}G(I)\right)\\
 & =1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

concluding the proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To complete the proof of formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
